"Ridgley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Buckinghamshire): habitational name from Rugeley (Staffordshire), from Old English <i>hrycg</i> ‘ridge’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’."],"variants":[{"name":"Ridgely","meanings":["English (Berkshire and Buckinghamshire): variant of   Ridgley  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Joyce","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the Norman male name <i>Josce</i> (Middle English <i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Joyce Ridgley was born in 1498, in Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom. She married William Hugh Harmon about 1520. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1531, in her hometown, at the age of 33."},"et":{"1498–1531":"1498–1531","1504–1530":"1504–1530","1486–1538":"1486–1538","1528–1583":"1528–1583","–Male":"Surnud","1498":"1498","1531":"1531","1486":"1486","1530":"1530","1583":"1583","about 1530":"umbes 1530","